<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Observer: Dial-a-stick
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's Foreign Office can perhaps be forgiven for drawing a blank in
trying to contact British nationals by telephone in Aden, southern Yemen,
where a confusing battle has been raging.
For the southern Yemenis, in a highly effective 'communications offensive'
against their northern enemies, have changed all telephone area codes to
their pre-unification digits. They have also declined to tell anyone what
the new/old codes are.
This cunning plot fell foul of a non-digitalised telephone exchange worker
in Aden. He informed a British Airways employee, who in turn contacted
London. There, the news spread swiftly to the small community of Indians
originally from Aden, one of whom informed the Foreign Office.
The moral? You never know when you might need your cleft stick.
</TEXT>
