FT  10 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Attitudes among the chattering classes towards Islamic fundamentalism
suggest that a liberal is someone who is incapable of taking his own side in
an argument. The appalling nature of these fanatics is as clear from the
newsreels showing children being taught to hit their own heads until they
bleed as it is from the fatwa against Salman Rushdie. Yet it is rare in this
country to hear Hizbollah condemned as mad, bad and deeply uncivilised. It
will be interesting to see what image emerges from Assignment's report on
'Allah's Army' (7.45 BBC2).
Last week's opening episode of Once Upon A Time In The North received some
remarkably good reviews. To me it looked like just another desperately
contrived sitcom, with the usual sit (widely diverse family group, Mum a a
heroine with common sense, Dad a hypocritical, ineffectual prat) and far too
little com (8.30 BBC1).
Whatever you may think of what is said on Without Walls you cannot deny that
they keep on coming up with interesting topics. Today Blake Morrison
considers attitudes towards childhood (9.00 C4).
