<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / BT plans to cut costs in rural areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications is extending its use of wireless technology to
cut network costs in rural areas.
BT has signed a contract with DSC, a US telecomm-unications equipment
supplier, for a wireless system to replace traditional copper wires in some
rural areas.
The move reflects the increasing attraction of radio systems as a
replacement for fixed-wire networks at local level. Ionica, a private
Cambridge-based company, is piloting a system in East Anglia which it plans
to introduce nationally.
Mercury, BT's main UK competitor, is engaged in radio experiments. It views
the technology as vital to bypassing BT's local network to carry its calls,
and predicts that within a few years 'millions' of subscribers will be
accessing its long-distance network through local radio systems.
DSC's digital radio system, Airspan, will allow BT to carry its full range
of services now carried over fixed lines with no reduction in quality. A
transmitter-receiver, less than one foot square, will be located at
subscribers' premises. The system has a range of 12 miles.
Until recently, radio technology in the telecoms industry was largely
restricted to paging and cellular mobile services. Suppliers are seeking to
exploit its potential, particularly in developing countries and
sparsely-populated areas.
</TEXT>
