<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Engineers call for tax allowance to boost innovation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new company tax allowance should be introduced to encourage innovation by
recognising the importance of professionally qualified engineers, scientists
and marketing staff, the Institution of Electrical Engineers said yesterday.
The plea was one of four linked national initiatives proposed in a report by
the institution which aim to improve the UK's output, productivity, share of
world trade and balance of payments.
It comes a few days before the long-awaited Department of Trade and Industry
white paper on competitiveness.
Professor Jack Levy, who prepared the institution's report, said: 'We hope
the DTI will take at least some of our ideas on board.'
The institution says innovation in research and development, design,
manufacturing and marketing depends crucially on the employment of qualified
people.
The new tax allowance would cover more than the total cost of employing
professionally qualified engineers, scientists and marketing staff plus
overheads and support.
As a starting point, the report suggests that 150 per cent of the cost of
such staff plus an agreed percentage for overheads should be allowed for tax
purposes.
The institution says there would be a number of immediate benefits:
innovation would be encouraged and the scheme would motivate staff and
employers.
It would also help combat the UK's anti-industrial culture.
Unveiling the report yesterday, Prof Levy said the initial cost of such a
scheme would be repaid in the long term through increased tax revenues from
an expanded manufacturing base.
The institution's innovation initiative also includes a plea for 100 per
cent capital allowances in the year of purchase to help companies re-equip
at the same rate as overseas competitors.
The three other proposals in the institution's Manufacturing Expansion
Scheme are initiatives on management, technology and finance for industry.
The finance proposal renews and expands on the institution's plea for a new
bank to enable small and medium-sized manufacturers to borrow money more
cheaply.
UK Manufacturing - Facing International Change. Publication Sales, IEE, PO
Box 96, Stevenage, Herts SG1 2SD. Free to IEE members, Pounds 20 to
non-members.
</TEXT>
