<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Commons warns of Scottish drug crisis
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Drug-related crime could be costing Scotland up to Pounds 936m a year, a
Commons committee said yesterday.
The cross-party committee of MPs said official figures on the drugs problem
represented 'the tip of the iceberg' and called for anti-drugs education to
start in primary schools.
One Glasgow GP told the Commons Scottish affairs committee that nearly half
the children at one secondary school class in his area had injected drugs.
The MPs' report calls for the painkiller Temgesic to be added to the list of
drugs of addiction notifiable to the Home Office.
It also calls on the Scottish Office to take a more active role in fighting
drug abuse, suggesting a wider use of 'needle exchanges' and crisis
intervention centres. But it would be 'foolhardy' to adopt any policy that
encouraged the use of cannabis. The report from the committee adds that the
Scottish Office estimates that about 20,000 people in Scotland inject
illicit or prescribed drugs.
The committee based its estimate of the cost of drug-related crime on
Glasgow's 8,500 injecting drug users each spending Pounds 300 a week on
drugs. Much of the cash came from the sale of stolen goods for about a third
of their true value. Projecting this Scotland-wide would imply a total of
Pounds 936m.
</TEXT>
