FT  10 MAY 94 / Prescott predicts drive to adopt minimum wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour is to make the introduction of a statutory national minimum wage one
of the main features of its economic policy in spite of differences over the
issue among unions.
The question is likely to have a prominent place in Labour's campaign in
next month's European elections and at the party's autumn conference. Mr
John Prescott, shadow employment secretary, told the MSF general technical
union at its conference yesterday that the party needed to back the general
principle of a national minimum wage, but should not yet commit itself to a
precise figure. He later said it would be necessary to agree on such a
figure before the next general election.
By focusing on the national minimum wage, Labour will be adopting a
high-risk strategy. Last month Mr Bill Morris, the TGWU's general secretary,
said a future Labour government should introduce a Pounds 4-an-hour national
minimum wage - a proposal denounced by the AEEU engineering union.
Many unions are concerned that any legally enforceable minimum wage will
lead to a squeeze on pay differentials and demands for pay rises to restore
relative pay positions. Observer, Page 17
