<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / How Household supplies will be opened up to competition
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Gas' monopoly of the domestic gas market will be ended in 1998, but
new competitors can start entering the market in 1996.
Safety: British Gas' transportation and storage division would retain 'a
prominent role' in ensuring the safety of the gas system.
Assurance of supply: any company with adequate resources would be eligible
to supply homes with gas. But suppliers will have to subscribe to a network
code to ensure orderly operation of the gas system.
Pricing: 'Some continuing regulation' may be necessary to aid the transition
to a competitive market, but prices could vary by plus or minus 2 to 4 per
cent for consumers because of different transportation costs.
Standards of service: new suppliers to observe same debt and disconnection
procedures as British Gas, and to have same obligation to supply older and
disabled customers for a time.
Other measures: liberalisation of metering, and incentives for efficient use
of gas.
</TEXT>
