<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / MPs win changes to bill on red tape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
De-regulation measures will be subject to greater parliamentary scrutiny
after the government said yesterday it would accept significant changes to
its bill.
The de-regulation bill would enable government departments to repeal
hundreds of regulatory measures without primary legislation.
Ministers have privately conceded that the bill, which has reached its
report stage in the Commons, is likely to face fierce opposition in the
Lords.
Critics of the bill have argued that parliamentary orders - which cannot be
amended and on which time for debate is limited - are not a suitable vehicle
for potentially complex and far-reaching changes in the law.
The cross-party Commons procedure committee had recommended tough new powers
for the select committee set up to scrutinise all de-regulation proposals.
In an attempt to placate critics, Mr Tim Sainsbury, trade and industry
minister, said the government would accept the committee's recommendation
for the new body, which will consider the final version of draft orders
implementing de-regulatory changes before they are debated by the Commons.
The bill requires ministers to wait 40 days between laying a draft order
before parliament and submitting a final draft for debate.
An amendment proposed by ministers would extend that period to 60 days if
the de-regulation committee felt that 40 days was not sufficient for
scrutiny of a proposal.
But some backbenchers remain concerned that the government could still push
through significant de-regulation measures without adequate scrutiny.
Mr Gary Waller, Tory MP for Keighley, said: 'While I support the objectives
behind the bill I am still not happy with the mechanism.'
</TEXT>
