<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Former BCCI executive in US on fraud charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Swaleh Naqvi, former chief executive of Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, appeared on fraud charges in a US court yesterday, after
being flown to the country on Saturday.
Mr Naqvi, who was number two at the bank under Mr Aga Hasan Abedi, BCCI's
founder, had been in custody in Abu Dhabi since soon after the bank was
closed in a worldwide swoop by regulators in July 1991. US prosecutors
secured his extradition in a January deal with Abu Dhabi authorities.
In federal court in Washington yesterday, Mr Naqvi pleaded not guilty to
four counts of fraud. These cover BCCI's alleged attempt to gain secret
control of a US bank, First American Bankshares, along with three other
financial institutions in the country.
If convicted, he could face a maximum of 31 years in jail and a Dollars
750,000 (Pounds 503,000) fine. Mr Naqvi was taken to jail pending a further
hearing on June 15. He has already pleaded guilty to fraud charges in Abu
Dhabi, but has not yet been sentenced. If sentenced to jail in both
countries, he would serve the US term first.
</TEXT>
