<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Lebanon clash over reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERUIT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lebanon's Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri and President Elias Hrawi locked
horns yesterday over a planned government reshuffle, Reuter reports from
Beirut. The prime minister cancelled tomorrow's cabinet meeting, prior to
greeting hundreds of supporters who flocked to his Beirut home in a show of
solidarity.
Last week, the two agreed to strengthen Christian representation in the
cabinet but have since disagreed over the extent of the reshuffle and the
new names to be brought in.
Relations between the Syrian-backed government and the once-dominant
Christian minority have been tense recently. The proposed changes appeared
an attempt to improve them by bringing in more representative Christian
politicians.
Political observers said Mr Hariri wanted to bring four new ministers into
the 30-member cabinet - two heavyweight Maronite Christian politicians
representing influential Christian political parties, a Sunni Moslem and a
Shi'ite Moslem. He also wanted to swap several portfolios, including
interior, defence and information, among the present ministers. Mr Hrawi was
pressing for a broader reshuffle, amounting to a reduction in Mr Hariri's
supporters in the cabinet.
