<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / Blackout obscures fighting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The confused military picture in Yemen's civil war was further darkened
yesterday by clouds of propaganda, with leaders in both north and south
claiming significant breakthroughs in battles concentrated around the
approaches to Aden, the southern capital.
Northern leaders claimed in Sanaa, North Yemen's capital, that their forces
were 'advancing on all fronts' and some units had reached Aden's Bar Saad
suburb, some 3 miles from the airport. The claims were dismissed in the
south, where spokesmen said they had 'totally destroyed' the northern
Amaliqa unit.
Independent assessments remained impossible, given the near-total
communications blackout. Western diplomats quoting reports from Sanaa said
the city was quiet, with no evidence of air or missile raids since those
launched by southern forces at the weekend.
Foreign governments continued to evacuate hundreds of expatriate workers,
with the French navy ferrying foreigners by warship from Aden to Djibouti. A
British Airways jet had landed at Sanaa airport to fly out 200 expatriates,
due at Gatwick airport last night.
