<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / UK beef imports face German ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany will tomorrow consider a unilateral move to ban the import of
British beef because of public concern over 'mad cow disease', in defiance
of the European Commission and the rest of the European Union.
A draft regulation to control beef imports will be submitted to the German
cabinet by Mr Horst Seehofer, the health minister, on the grounds that a
form of the disease - bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - may possibly
be communicated to humans. The German government is pressing ahead with the
ban, in spite of warnings from Brussels that it will face injunctions and
legal action in the European Court of Justice. Its own experts have also
expressed doubt that any unilateral ban can be effectively enforced because
of the EU's open borders. But health ministry officials insisted yesterday
that the measure will be enacted and can be put into effect.
In London, Mrs Gillian Shephard, the British agriculture minister, said a
unilateral ban on British beef by Germany would be unjustifiable and illegal
under the Treaty of Rome. Britain would take court action if necessary
against Germany for creating an unfair trade barrier, but it looked to the
European Commission to take action in the first instance, she said. Mr
Dieter Vogel, for the German government, said yesterday: 'We have always
said we would prefer to find a common solution for this BSE problem. If that
is not possible, then we have to find a unilateral solution. It may be that
the cabinet will decide on this on Wednesday.
'We are not in favour of unilateral solutions, but in the worst case we will
have to find one.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
