<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 94 / BBC to link with Pearson in world satellite TV project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC and Pearson, the media and entertainment group, are expected to
announce today that they have formed a worldwide strategic alliance to
develop satellite television channels and other joint ventures.
The grouping could be a growing challenge to international broadcasters such
as Mr Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation and Mr Ted Turner's Cable News
Network.
The launch later this year will be a 24-hour BBC World Service Television
channel for Europe, but further channels for Europe and other continents,
particularly Asia, will follow.
The announcement precedes the white paper on the future of the corporation,
which has now been delayed until next month. This suggests that the BBC
argument that it should be able to expand internationally has been accepted.
The government will insist, however, that licence fee money should not be
used for commercial ventures and on transparent accounting.
Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, is likely to provide a scale of
financial investment that the BBC is unable to provide. The corporation has
one of the largest news organisations in the world and an enormous programme
library, which it is keen to exploit.
Recently Pearson has made it clear that its future is as a broadly-based
media and entertainment group. It acquired Thames Television, the former
holder of the London weekday TV franchise, but pulled out of a potential
purchase of Star TV, the Asian satellite venture now controlled by Mr
Murdoch.
Under an agreement with Mr Murdoch, the BBC has already left the northern
beam of the Star system and is no longer available in Hong Kong and China.
It loses the right to broadcast its World Television channel on the southern
beam, which covers India, next year. A return to Asia in a joint venture
with Pearson is now likely.
Apart from areas such as news and documentaries, collaboration could include
education channels and language tuition.
It is believed that a separate company will be set up by the BBC to handle
any ventures with Pearson. The two groups will bring in other local partners
in different parts of the world.
The BBC has been looking for a significant commercial partner for some time
and considered a wide range of possible partners. But Pearson was seen as
the most complementary.
Neither senior BBC or Pearson executives could be reached for comment last
night.
Reuter starts TV service, Page 9
</TEXT>
