<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Kemper bows to higher GE offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kemper, the US investment group, yesterday bowed to an unwanted takeover
approach from GE Capital after the General Electric financial services arm
increased its offer for the company to Dollars 2.4bn (Pounds 1.64bn).
GE Capital, which had first offered Dollars 55 a share for the company in
March, overcame the resistance of Kemper's board by raising its bid to
Dollars 60 a share.
The agreement, announced jointly by the two companies yesterday, comes just
three days before Kemper shareholders were due to vote on whether to appoint
four GE Capital nominees to their company's board. If approved, this would
have put irresistible pressure on the Long Grove, Illinois-based company to
agree a sale.
The agreed deal will turn GE Capital into one of the US's biggest fund
management groups. Kemper, whose operations span life insurance, mutual
funds and securities broking, had Dollars 67.4bn under management at the end
of March.
Kemper's shareholders had been pressing for a higher offer than the initial
Dollars 55 a share. Although publicly backing the rejection of GE Capital's
opening offer, some of the company's institutional shareholders had hinted
they would consider a higher bid.
In an attempt to appease the institutions, Mr David Mathis, Kemper's
chairman, last week said the company would poll shareholders a year from now
on a possible sale, if the company's share price had failed to reach Dollars
65. It appears this assurance could not overcome the attraction of an
immediate sale. Many of Kemper's shares are believed to have passed in
recent weeks to arbitrageurs, who buy shares in the hope of a quick profit
from events such as takeovers.
Mr Mathis's letter had added to a belief that Kemper's board would accept an
immediate offer of Dollars 65 a share. However, the GE Capital bid failed to
flush out any rival offers, as some Kemper executives had hoped, and even at
Dollars 60 a share the deal is well above the Dollars 40 level at which
Kemper was trading until mid-March.
GE Capital said its new offer was dependent on a review of Kemper's troubled
Dollars 1.7bn real estate portfolio, and outstanding litigation against the
company. It had earlier said that it might be prepared to raise the Dollars
55 a share offer, subject to a review of the real estate investments.
The Kemper annual meeting, which was due on Wednesday, has been postponed
until August 22.
Global Investor, Page 22
</TEXT>
