<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Company News (This Week): UK insurers likely to confirm
recovery - Other companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Three of the UK's biggest insurance companies are due to report rises in
profits for the first quarter, confirming recovery in that market. General
Accident is expected tomorrow to post pre-tax profits of about Pounds 60m,
compared with Pounds 42m. Forecasts for Commercial Union's profits on
Wednesday vary from Pounds 38m to Pounds 80m, while the range is Pounds
15m-Pounds 50m for Royal Insurance the same day. Some analysts warn,
however, that current profit levels do not represent any increase on the
last quarter of 1993 and suggest that competition is returning to some
sectors of the market.
Kwik Save: The UK's largest grocery discounter is expected to report interim
pre-tax profits of Pounds 62m-Pounds 64m, against Pounds 61m. While it is
one of those putting pressure on J Sainsbury, it faces competition on its
own territory from expanding continental discounters.
Scottish Power: The electricity generator and distributor is expected to
reveal annual pre-tax profits of Pounds 340m-Pounds 350m on Wednesday, up
from Pounds 308m. The total dividend will probably rise by 11 per cent to
12.4p.
Royal Bank of Scotland: The bank, reporting on Wednesday, is expected to
double its interim pre-tax profits, which stood at Pounds 91.6m last time,
as well as lift its dividend. Questions will include whether it will spend
its healthy capital on acquisition.
Grand Metropolitan: Interim figures, due on Thursday from the food and
drinks group, should show a 10 per cent increase to about Pounds 445m
pre-tax. The Pillsbury Green Giant business in the US should do well, given
the floods in the mid-west and the resulting rise in vegetable prices. The
hot topic is whether GrandMet will unwind its unhappy Inntrepreneur pubs
joint venture with Courage.
Unilever: First-quarter figures on Friday for the Anglo-Dutch consumer
products group should show modest improvement to about Pounds 450m pre-tax,
against Pounds 440m, with detergents the main depressing factor. A downturn
in the US started after the period and this quarter should also start to
show the costs of launching a new concentrated detergent across Europe.
</TEXT>
