<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Household and business debts could slow economic growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
High levels of household and company debt will curb borrowing, investment
and employment growth during the present economic recovery, the Bank of
England warns today.
The Bank calculates that in the first quarter of this year more than 1.29m
households were affected by negative equity, with their mortgage borrowings
exceeding the value of their property.
The total value of negative equity was Pounds 7.6bn, representing an average
of Pounds 5,900 per affected household, the Bank says.
At its peak in the first quarter of 1993, the negative equity of home-buyers
totalled nearly Pounds 12bn and affected about 1.8m households, of which
more than half were in the south-east.
In an article, released before publication tomorrow of its Quarterly
Bulletin and Inflation Report, the Bank says the continuing effects of high
debt levels are likely to lead to cautious borrowing patterns and moves to
reduce debt in the months ahead.
In the longer term the Bank expects households and corporations to be
willing to take on debt again.
In the personal sector, income gearing - the ratio of net interest payments
to disposable income - is back at the levels of the mid-1980s while the
corporate sector as a whole has reduced its indebtedness sharply since 1992.
But, says the Bank: 'In the recent recession, debt had a much greater impact
on both sectors' behaviour than in the recession of the early 1980s.' House
price falls and debt deflation 'left many recent house-buyers - a
substantial minority of all homeowners, and often young, first-time buyers -
with negative net wealth'.
In the corporate sector, the Bank found that smaller companies were
especially badly hit by high levels of debt. Many companies became
vulnerable to recession through over-expansion in the 1980s when they had
high profit expectations that were not fulfilled.
The Bank says the financial hardships experienced by households have changed
spending patterns and affected the economy as a whole.
For example, lump sum repayments to mortgage lenders rose by 140 per cent
between 1989 and 1993 to reach Pounds 2.5bn, or nearly 5 per cent of
personal sector saving last year.
This increase, at a time of falling mortgage rates, almost certainly
reflected concern among borrowers about debt levels being too high.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
