<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Dismay at stance on EU funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is refusing to submit plans for spending Pounds 520m of
European Union funds available to the UK for retraining workers in
industries undergoing structural change - such as cars and carpets.
Ministers believe that the money would be better spent on training for the
unemployed and that employee training is the responsibility of employers.
But the decision has caused dismay among local authorities, motor industry
companies and Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) in areas of industrial
change such as the Midlands.
'When funding is already there and we're turning our back on it, it is
extremely frustrating,' said Mr John Hawksby, a Bedfordshire Conservative
councillor who is chairman of the all-party Motor Industry Local Authority
Network (Milan), which brings together local authorities with a strong
interest in the motor industry.
The money available from the EU is the so-called Objective Four funding,
which can be spent over the next five years. It is administered by national
governments, which must give the European Commission details of their
spending plans. The UK government has refused to do this for 1995-96.
'We believe that the money could be better used in helping the unemployed
under Objective Three of the structural funds, which provides training for
the unemployed,' the employment department said.
Any money spent on Objective Four funding comes out of the budget for
Objective Three. By not applying for Objective Four funds, the government
hopes to maintain present levels of EU funding for unemployment programmes.
However, Mr Rodney Skidmore, chief executive of Central England Training and
Enterprise Council, said that withholding Objective Four funds was making it
harder for Tecs to assist in reskilling local labour forces. 'Anything we
can do to help people make a smooth transition in employment must make
sense.'
Motor industry groups, including Ford, Vauxhall, Unipart and Rover - which
spends Pounds 35m a year on training - want to tap Objective Four funding.
Mr Iain Mills, co-chairman of the Commons car industry committee, said it
would not take up any position on the issue before the autumn.
</TEXT>
