<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Resignation of whip 'won't harm Major'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative party managers insisted yesterday that the resignation of a
government whip over allegations of a homo-sexual relationship would do
little to harm Mr John Major's already beleaguered government.
Mr Michael Brown, the Tory MP for Brigg and Cleethorpes, announced at the
weekend that he would return to the back benches after a Sunday newspaper
alleged that he had a homosexual relationship with a Tory student.
An official at Conservative Central Office described the allegations, which
appeared in the News of the World, as a 'storm in a teacup'. Members of the
MP's constituency party also pledged to stand by him, indicating there would
be no question of Mr Brown being asked to resign his seat.
However, the MP is the latest in a long line of Tory ministers and MPs who
have been forced to resign following the launch of the 'Back to Basics'
drive.
In the last six months, two ministers and one parliamentary private
secretary have resigned in the wake of allegations about their private lives
in British newspapers.
Mr Brown is a leading member of the 'No Turning Back' group of Tory
rightwingers. He was promoted to the whips' office last May with special
responsibility for Northern Ireland, transport and the north west of
England. Before that, in 1989, he was appointed parliamentary private
secretary to Mr Douglas Hogg, then trade and industry minister, staying with
him when he went to the Foreign Office.
But although a loyal Thatcherite, he was not above rebelling against Lady
Thatcher's government when he thought it was moving in the wrong direction -
particularly over Europe.
The revelations over his personal life - which he is disputing - could
hardly have come at a worse time for the government, following the
catastrophic result for the Conservatives in the local government elections
and with the Euro-elections to be held next month.
</TEXT>
