<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Ex-Tory voters say PM must go
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Most ex-Conservative voters want Mr John Major to resign, according to a
Gallup opinion poll conducted for the BBC.
In a poll of 988 people who voted Tory in the 1992 general election, 58 per
cent said Mr Major should resign, while just 34 per cent said he should stay
on. All 988 people polled said they would not or were not inclined to vote
Tory if there were a general election tomorrow.
Among this group of voters, the Conservatives are less trusted on tax than
Labour, the poll found. Eighty eight per cent said they would not believe a
Conservative politician talking about taxes, while 82 per cent would not
trust a Labour politician on the subject.
Mr Michael Heseltine was the preferred choice to replace Mr Major, with 34
per cent of these former Tory voters saying they would vote Conservative if
he were party leader. Only 18 per cent in each case would vote Conservative
if either Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, or Mr Michael Portillo, chief
secretary, were in charge.
</TEXT>
