<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Scheme for school leavers supported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Almost two-thirds of young people believe the government should introduce a
community service scheme for all school leavers, a survey shows today.
The study, conducted by Gallup for the charity CSV which places young people
in voluntary posts, shows that 64 per cent of 16 to 24-year-olds believe the
government should establish a voluntary programme available to all young
people.
Although community service has supporters among individual politicians, the
parties have tended to shy away from the idea - particularly in any form
that might look like the introduction of a compulsory alternative to
national service.
The poll showed that 31 per cent believe that community service for school
leavers should be compulsory.
'Over 6m carers nationwide need respite care and support,' said Ms Elisabeth
Hoodless, executive director of CSV. 'Schools in our inner cities would be
transformed if each pupil had a volunteer mentor or tutor to help with their
reading. Crime would be cut by giving young people the chance to put their
energy and enthusiasm to good use.'
</TEXT>
