<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Union finds high level of worker dissatisfaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A high level of dissatisfaction with employers' treatment of their workers
is recorded in a workplace opinion survey published today by the MSF general
technical union.
Nearly half the sample of MSF's workplace representatives said the treatment
of staff in their workplace by management was either or poor or very poor
compared with 11 per cent who thought it was good or better. The highest
levels of dissatisfaction were among sales staff (65 per cent) and
administrative and clerical (51 per cent).
The survey also found that 37 per cent of employees feared their jobs were
less secure than three months ago, with the highest level of anxiety about
jobs being experienced in the financial services sector and the National
Health Service.
However, 28 per cent of MSF representatives described relations between the
unions and employers as good or very good and 44 per cent said they were
fair. By contrast, 28 per cent said relations were poor or very poor with 17
per cent reporting a deterioration in union/management relations.
The survey was carried out for MSF by the independent organisation Quality
Data Preparation. It covered representatives in 404 private and
public-sector workplaces. A MORI poll conducted for the GMB general union
identified concern over unemployment as the main factor in the way people
voted in the recent local government elections.
The survey of 501 people showed that for 69 per cent, policies on creating
jobs and reducing unemployment had been crucial in determining their vote.
Mr John Edmonds, GMB general secretary, said: 'Fear of unemployment is the
iceberg that will sink this government.'
</TEXT>
