<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Gummer seeks to revitalise town centres
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, will reinforce his commitment to
revitalising town centres this week with a report which warns that property
owners and financial institutions must invest in cities or risk them
becoming US-style 'ghost towns'.
Mr Gummer will launch the government-sponsored report, the result of a
year-long study, at the Cities 94 urban regeneration conference in London's
Docklands tomorrow. .
The report warns that cities face a choice between the North American
example, where retailing has been sucked out of many town centres by
out-of-town developments, and the continental European model, where high
population density, good transport facilities and attractive streets have
kept city centres popular.
The report's recommendations stress the need for property owners and
investors, including insurance companies, banks and building societies, to
play a part in regenerating urban centres.
If that is not achieved voluntarily, it suggests, the only solution might be
US-style business development districts, where property owners must pay a
local levy to fund town-centre promotion and improvements in the urban
environment.
Mr Gummer has already published two controversial guidance notes for local
authorities, PPG6 and PPG13, emphasising the importance of restricting
development of greenfield sites and restor-ing the vitality of town centres.
The new report - by the Urban and Economic Development Group, the planning
consultancy, and four other partners - explores ways of achieving the latter
and of assessing the impact on town centres of edge-of town and out-of-town
developments.
It recommends that local authorities produce a 'town profile', a vision of
where the town should be going, and a strategy to support it. It adds that
local authorities should also set up town-centre management groups, bringing
together local officials as well as forums representing all the main
interests including councillors and officials, retailers, chambers of
commerce, property owners and community groups.
A report published today by Corporate Intelligence, the retail research
group, warns that the government's tougher stance on out-of-town retailing
could threaten the development of US-style factory outlet centres and thus
restrict consumer choice.
It says nearly 30 such centres, which group together manufacturers' shops
selling branded goods at low prices, are proposed in the UK, but several may
not receive planning permission under the new rules.
</TEXT>
