<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Doubt on upturn in construction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Civil engineers are becoming concerned that the construction recovery may be
starting to lose pace, says a survey of more than 130 companies published
today.
The survey by the Federation of Civil Engineering Contractors shows that
there has been a disturbing decline in invitations to tender for work during
the first three months of this year.
Mr John Hackett, federation director-general, said the findings were mixed:
'Some of the answers were the best we have received for four years.
'There has been some further improvement in orders actually won and there
has been the first sign of an increase in jobs. On the other hand, cost
increases are accelerating and threatening to reverse the easing of the
squeeze on contractors' margins.'
The proportion of companies reporting a fall in invitations to tender
compared with 12 months earlier has increased from 18 per cent to 27 per
cent since the previous survey published at the beginning of this year. The
proportion reporting a rise in tender invitations has fallen from 43 per
cent to 27 per cent.
Mr Hackett said: 'With our members aware that the Department of Transport
will be starting fewer new road schemes in 1994-95 than in 1993-94; that
English local authorities' road spending plans have been hit by the savage
cut in transport supplementary grants; and that the English and Welsh water
industry has been holding back on investment pending the outcome of Ofwat's
price limits review, it is hardly surprising we have found members less
confident than previously about prospects for the coming 12 months.
'With additional orders already in the book it looks as if the recent slight
recovery in employment may hold up through 1994, but once again we have a
majority of firms fearing that the flow of new orders will tail off over the
coming year.'
The federation said that much of the recent rise in new orders had been due
to a few large projects such as the extension to London Underground's
Jubilee Line. These orders were very welcome but benefited relatively few
contractors, it added.
</TEXT>
