<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Pay deal analyses differ on growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Differing analyses of the recent upward trend in pay settlements are
published today by two of the most influential pay analysis organisations.
Incomes Data Services says that the upward trend looks set to continue with
a growing proportion of April settlements giving increases of between 3 per
cent and 3.5 per cent.
Industrial Relations Services, however, says that the upturn may now be
levelling out. It finds that settlements are remaining steady at 2.5 per
cent and that upward pressures 'seem unlikely to intensify much further over
the months ahead'.
Among the April rises monitored by IDS are 3 per cent increases at Toshiba,
3 per cent average merit awards at the Co-operative Bank and 4.5 per cent
average merit rises for clerical staff at Lloyds Bank.
Overall in the banking sector pay rises in 1994 have ranged between 1.6 per
cent and 4.5 per cent, with awards increasing in the course of the year.
Retail pay rises are slightly lower, with most between 2 per cent and 3 per
cent.
An indication that more companies have confidence inflation will remain
steady comes from the growth in pay deals covering more than one year. IDS
says that two-year agreements have recently been agreed at British Airways,
McVitie's, Chivas Brothers, Pilkington Optronics and Cummins Engine's Shotts
site.
A two-year deal at Massey Ferguson, the tractor maker, has also explicitly
recognised the impact of this year's tax increases by giving a higher
flat-rate rise of Pounds 12 for this year compared with Pounds 10 for next.
IDS Report 664, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS. IRS Pay and Benefits
Bulletin 351. 18-29 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
