FT  09 MAY 94 / North-east England quoted company sector gains momentum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The importance of the quoted company sector in north-east England increased
significantly last year, demonstrating that the region's economy has
regained momentum, a survey by accountancy firm Price Waterhouse has found,
Chris Tighe writes.
The north-east's quoted companies recorded turnover of Pounds 3.5bn last
year, up 12 per cent on 1992. Pre-tax profits grew 30 per cent to Pounds
326m. In the 1980s, 23 of the quoted companies disappeared because of
takeovers, receiverships and relocations but the survey says this trend now
appears to have been reversed. At the end of last year the region had 29
quoted companies, two more than a year before. There are now 30 and another
flotation is planned this summer.
