<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Consumer spending drop blamed on tax rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the first signs that April's tax increases could be sapping consumer
confidence emerged yesterday, with the release of figures showing a surge in
consumer borrowing in March - but a drop in discretionary spending in April.
Data published by two credit organisations point to increased credit levels
in the retail, car and home-loans sectors in March as consumers apparently
ignored the impending tax rises.
But figures released by Barclaycard, which represents 38 per cent of UK
credit card spending, suggest the tax increases incorporated in April's pay
packets are now reducing discretionary spending.
The figures, which show the amounts processed by Barclaycard on any given
day - indicating spending on that day or immediately before - suggest
spending has dropped slightly compared with the equivalent period last year.
On April 25, the amount processed by Barclaycard was 120 per cent of the
amount processed on Monday, April 26 last year. By May 5, the cumulative
figure over the previous two weeks had slipped to 106 per cent of the
comparable 1993 figure.
Mr Michael Head, who is in charge of planning and development at
Barclaycard, admitted that the figures were 'not very exciting'.
He added that, although consumers appeared to have discounted much of the
impact of April's tax increases in the period since the November Budget,
there could still be further slippage. 'It looks as though there may just be
a slight tightening of the screw,' he said.
This concern, however, is at odds with an upbeat message in a report
published today by the Finance and Leasing Association on consumer credit in
March, before the tax rises were introduced. The association represents
companies accounting for 80 per cent of consumer credit and 30 per cent of
business investment in plant and equipment.
Total consumer credit rose to Pounds 1,463m in March, a growth of 44 per
cent year-on-year (and 19 per cent compared with February), the association
said.
The biggest growth occurred in the retail sector, where purchases on store
cards grew 57 per cent year-on-year, and 34 per cent month-on-month. Credit
in the motor sector grew 37 per cent and personal loans rose 34 per cent
year-on-year.
The publication of these figures follows a weekend report by Infolink, the
credit information organisation, which also found a credit surge and
concluded that in March 'consumers remained unperturbed by April's impending
tax increases'.
The finance association also noted that the rise in business credit was
relatively subdued, with an 8 per cent growth in business finance
year-on-year - lower than previous months.
Mr Tony Mallin, the association's chairman, said: 'The business figures for
March are disappointing . . . in our view businesses are still not investing
as much as we would have expected at this point in the cycle.'
</TEXT>
