<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Debt threatens investment, says Bank: Quarterly Bulletin
warns cautious borrowing likely - Asset-backed securities market grows
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Norman, Economics Editor
Severe financial constraints affecting a minority of UK households and
companies are likely to lead to cautious borrowing patterns and moves to
reduce debt in the months ahead, the Bank of England warns today.
In an article released before publication tomorrow of its Quarterly Bulletin
and Inflation Report, the Bank concludes that the continuing effects of high
debt levels on some companies could dampen investment and employment
expansion during the present economic recovery.
In the longer term the Bank expects households and corporations will be
willing to take on debt again.
In the personal sector, income gearing - the ratio of net interest payments
to disposable income - is back at the levels of the mid 1980s while the
corporate sector as a whole has reduced its indebtedness sharply since 1992.
But, says the Bank, 'in the recent recession, debt had a much greater impact
on both sectors' behaviour than in the recession of the early 1980s.
'Even last year, many companies remained vulnerable to a sharp rise in
interest rates.' House price falls and debt deflation 'left many recent
housebuyers - a substantial minority of all homeowners, and often young,
first-time buyers - with negative net wealth'.
At its peak in the first quarter of 1993, the negative equity of homebuyers
totalled nearly Pounds 12bn and affected about 1.8m households, of which
more than half were in the south-east.
In the first quarter of this year, negative equity was still affecting 1.29m
households. Its total value was Pounds 7.6bn, representing an average of
Pounds 5,900 per affected household, the Bank says.
In the corporate sector, the Bank found that smaller companies were
especially badly hit by high levels of debt. Many companies became
vulnerable to recession through over-expansion in the 1980s when they had
high profit expectations that were not fulfilled.
One analysis showed that 'the firms that were highly indebted in 1991 had
been among the most profitable in the mid 1980s'.
The combination of debt and poor profitability among highly geared companies
led in the recession to large-scale job losses, cuts in investment and
widespread insolvency. A substantial minority of households had mortgage
arrears and some lost their homes through repossession.
The Bank says the financial hardships experienced by households have changed
spending patterns and affected the economy as a whole. For example, lump-sum
repayments to mortgage lenders rose by 140 per cent between 1989 and 1993 to
Pounds 2.5bn, or nearly 5 per cent of personal sector saving last year. This
increase, at a time of falling mortgage rates, almost certainly reflected
concern about debt levels.
</TEXT>
