<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / US relaxes stance on Haitians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton said yesterday the US would stop sending fleeing
Haitians home without an asylum hearing, reversing a policy that some
critics had condemned as racist, Reuter reports from Washington.
Mr Clinton said he had ordered the change, to become effective shortly,
because of what he called stepped-up repression of the Haitian people by
Haiti's military rulers.
'The Haitian people will see we are not opening the floodgates to
indiscriminate refugee migration into the US but that we are going to try to
find those people who have left because they have a genuine fear,' he said.
'I hope that we will not have a flood of refugees but we are increasing our
naval resources to deal with that.'
Mr Clinton said the criteria for considering claims for political asylum
would remain unchanged. 'We will determine aboard ship or in other countries
which ones are bona fide political refugees,' he said in a briefing for
reporters at the White House Rose Garden.
Previously, the US had granted asylum hearings only to those who applied at
processing centres in Haiti, intercepting boats at sea and sending back
others without a hearing on their asylum claim.
</TEXT>
