<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 94 / Banks to dispense adverts with cash in the high street
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two high street banks are poised to cash in on their cash dispensers by
selling advertising space and issuing discount vouchers.
Instead of a vacantly blinking 'Welcome, please insert your card' sign,
customers will be met with an advertisement, whether for a local shop or a
national product. Money-off coupons will be dispensed with the cash. It is
likely that banks will combat criticism about potential litter by allowing
customers to opt not to receive the vouchers.
Two high street banks in the UK are planning to test the scheme later this
year at about 150 cash dispensers, according to Aimmedia International, the
Kingston upon Thames, Surrey-based company which has developed the system.
If the three-month trials are successful, the company hopes to market the
system to other UK banks which together have more than 18,000 dispensers.
Advertisers will pay an average of Pounds 110 a week for the exclusive use
of a cash machine, which will issue a maximum of 2,000 vouchers during the
week.
It will be possible to target particular cash machines to maximise the
effect of the advertising; for example, a dispenser near a large music shop
might issue vouchers for compact discs and audio tapes.
On the reverse side of the vouchers, banks will print their own, possibly
linked, advertising. A voucher redeemable against a holiday, say, could also
advertise travellers' cheques; a car test-drive offer might also promote the
bank's car loans.
In the US, the National Bank of Commerce, Tennessee, is testing out the
idea, and Aimmedia plans to approach banks in Spain, Portugal, Italy, France
and Scandinavia. Building societies could also be attracted to the scheme,
the company believes.
Mr Steve Ross, Aimmedia's managing director, said the advertising offered
banks the chance to make money out of their costly dispensers. Manufacturers
and retailers would be able to target consumers in the high street. 'A
computerised geographical information system will allow the advertiser to
specify the machines their vouchers are dispensed from,' he said.
Household and business debts could slow growth, Page 18
</TEXT>
